(40, 19, 28, 40, 16, 27, 27, 'the Son of man shall sit', 'Connection of Reward and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of reward associated with the coming of the Son of man. Matthew 19:28 speaks of followers judging the tribes of Israel, while Matthew 16:27 mentions rewarding every man according to his works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 42, 18, 29, 30, 'for my name's sake', 'Rewards for Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the rewards for those who leave family and possessions for God''s sake. They highlight the promise of receiving much more in this life and eternal life to come.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 41, 10, 29, 30, 'for my name's sake', 'Connection of Sacrifice and Reward', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forsaking familial and material ties for Jesus'' sake, promising a hundredfold return and eternal life. This connection highlights the shared message of sacrifice leading to divine reward.', 'theme', 0.8879999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 50, 3, 8, 8, 'forsaken houses, or brethren, or sisters', 'Loss for Christ''s Sake', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forsaking worldly attachments for the sake of Christ. Matthew speaks of forsaking family and lands, while Philippians highlights counting all things as loss to gain Christ.', 'theme', 0.804, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 42, 14, 26, 26, NULL, 'Discipleship and Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the cost of discipleship, highlighting the necessity of prioritizing Jesus above familial ties and personal attachments. They illustrate the theme of sacrifice for the sake of following Christ.', 'theme', 0.72, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 40, 16, 25, 25, NULL, 'Sacrifice for Christ''s Sake', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of losing one''s life or possessions for the sake of Jesus. Matthew 19:29 speaks of forsaking everything for His name, while Matthew 16:25 highlights losing one''s life for His sake. This connection highlights the reward of eternal life for such sacrifices.', 'theme', 0.692, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 40, 10, 37, 38, 'forsaken houses, or brethren, or sisters', 'Sacrifice for Christ''s Sake', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of prioritizing Jesus over familial ties. They highlight the theme of forsaking personal relationships and comforts for the sake of following Him.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 60, 4, 14, 14, 'for my name's sake', 'Reproach and Reward for Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of suffering for Christ''s name and the subsequent rewards. Matthew highlights the sacrifices made for Jesus, while 1 Peter speaks to the joy found in being reproached for His name.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 40, 20, 16, 16, NULL, 'First and Last Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, stating that ''the first shall be last'' and ''the last shall be first.'' This connection highlights a consistent theme of humility and divine selection.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 42, 13, 30, 30, 'first shall be last; and the last shall be first', 'First and Last Concept', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where those considered last may become first and vice versa. This connection highlights a shared theme of humility and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 41, 10, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Last and First', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, stating that ''the first shall be last; and the last first.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of humility and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 40, 21, 31, 32, 'first shall be last', 'First and Last in Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of expectations regarding who enters the kingdom of God. The first shall be last, as seen in the publicans and harlots entering before the religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 42, 18, 13, 14, 'the last shall be first', 'Humility and Exaltation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status based on humility and pride. Matthew highlights that ''the last shall be first,'' while Luke illustrates this through the publican''s humble plea for mercy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 45, 5, 20, 21, 'first shall be last', 'Grace and Reversal of Status', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where those who seem first may ultimately be last, and where sin''s abundance is overshadowed by grace. This connection highlights the transformative power of grace in the context of human failure and societal expectations.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 45, 9, 30, 33, NULL, 'Righteousness and Reversal of Status', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where those who are considered last, like the Gentiles, attain righteousness through faith, while those who are first, like Israel, fail due to reliance on the law. This connection highlights the theme of unexpected outcomes in God''s plan for salvation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 40, 13, 24, 24, 'the kingdom of heaven', 'Parables of the Kingdom', 'Both passages emphasize the kingdom of heaven and use the imagery of a man who engages in work related to agriculture. This connection highlights the theme of God''s active role in establishing His kingdom through labor and sowing.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 40, 13, 47, 47, 'kingdom of heaven', 'Kingdom of Heaven Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of the kingdom of heaven through metaphorical comparisons. The householder hiring laborers and the net gathering fish illustrate the inclusive and active nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 22, 8, 11, 12, 'vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard and the labor associated with it. The householder in Matthew hires laborers for his vineyard, while Solomon''s vineyard is managed by keepers who are compensated for their work.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 58, 13, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Work and Will', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor and divine purpose. Both passages emphasize the importance of working in alignment with God''s will, as seen in the laborers hired for the vineyard and the call to do good works in Hebrews.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 23, 5, 1, 2, 'vineyard', 'Vineyard Imagery Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, representing God''s work and expectations. The householder in Matthew hires laborers for his vineyard, paralleling the beloved''s care for the vineyard in Isaiah.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 43, 15, 1, 1, 'vineyard', 'Connection of Vineyard Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a vineyard, with Matthew describing a householder hiring laborers for his vineyard and John identifying God as the husbandman of the true vine. This connection highlights the agricultural imagery used to illustrate roles within the kingdom of heaven.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 1, 46, 15, 58, 58, 'labourers into his vineyard', 'Connection of Labor in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of labor in both passages. Matthew 20:1 speaks of hiring laborers for a vineyard, while 1 Corinthians 15:58 encourages steadfastness in the work of the Lord, assuring that such labor is not in vain.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 2, 19, 5, 6, 'agreed with the labourers', 'Obedience and Reward', 'This connection highlights the theme of agreement and reward for labor. In both passages, there is an emphasis on fulfilling a covenant or agreement, leading to a promised status or reward.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 5, 5, 27, 30, 'agreed with the labourers', 'Labor and Obedience Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of agreement and obedience. In Matthew, the laborers agree to work for a wage, while in Deuteronomy, the people agree to hear and do the Lord''s commands.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 9, 2, 18, 18, NULL, 'Service and Labor in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of service, as both passages depict individuals engaged in labor for a greater purpose. In Matthew, the laborers are sent into the vineyard, while Samuel is described as ministering before the Lord, emphasizing dedication to their respective tasks.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 9, 2, 26, 26, NULL, 'Growth and Favor in Service', 'This connection highlights the theme of growth and favor in service. Both passages emphasize the importance of being in favor, whether with the Lord or in fulfilling one''s duties.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 11, 3, 6, 11, NULL, 'Understanding and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of discernment and understanding in fulfilling one''s role. In Matthew, the laborers are given a clear agreement for their work, while Solomon seeks wisdom to judge his people effectively.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 11, 18, 12, 12, NULL, 'Labor and Divine Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of service and obedience to a higher authority. In both passages, the laborers and the servant demonstrate a commitment to their tasks, reflecting a reliance on divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 2, 14, 34, 3, 3, 'sent them into his vineyard', 'Labor and Seeking God', 'This connection highlights the theme of commitment to a task, as seen in both passages. In Matthew, the laborers agree to work in the vineyard, while in 2 Chronicles, the young king commits to purging idolatry from Judah.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 3, 54, 5, 13, 13, 'standing idle', 'Idleness and Its Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of idleness present in both passages. In Matthew, individuals are described as ''standing idle,'' while in 1 Timothy, idleness leads to negative behaviors such as gossiping.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
